---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import ArchitectureDiagram from '../components/ArchitectureDiagram.astro';
---

<Base
	title="ContextAgora: notes on context engineering"
	description="A short primer on context engineering: why the unit of work is shifting from the product to the context, what a context module looks like on disk, and how an agent reads one. With a sandbox and a self-host path so you can try the ideas."
>

	<!-- Hero -->
	<section class="mb-16 sm:mb-20 text-center pt-12 sm:pt-20">
		<p class="text-xs font-medium text-text-muted uppercase tracking-widest mb-6">
			Notes on context engineering
		</p>
		<h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-semibold text-accent tracking-tight mb-6 leading-[1.1]">
			From product-centered to context-centered.
		</h1>
		<p class="text-base text-text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mx-auto">
			For decades the unit of development was the product: a feature, a screen, a workflow. With agents in the loop, it shifts. What you ship is the context the agent reads before it acts: docs, schemas, runbooks, scoped secrets, all bundled into a folder it can find. ContextAgora is where we work out what that looks like, in the open.
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- Architecture diagram -->
	<section class="mb-16 sm:mb-20">
		<ArchitectureDiagram />
	</section>

	<!-- Concept blocks -->
	<section class="mb-16 sm:mb-20 text-center">
		<dl class="space-y-10 max-w-xl mx-auto">
			<div>
				<dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-text mb-2">The context module is the unit.</dt>
				<dd class="text-sm text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">A folder with a manifest, the docs the agent should read, and pointers to the secrets it will need. You stop writing integrations; you write modules, and the agent figures out the integration from what is in the folder.</dd>
			</div>
			<div>
				<dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-text mb-2">The agent reads an index, not the world.</dt>
				<dd class="text-sm text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">Every module ships an <code class="font-mono text-accent">llms.txt</code>: a short reading list that tells the agent what is in the folder and where to look first. The agent starts there and pulls only what the task needs. No prompt-stuffing, no stale exports.</dd>
			</div>
			<div>
				<dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-text mb-2">Secrets are scoped to the task.</dt>
				<dd class="text-sm text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">API keys live in a vault, never in the prompt and never in the repo. The agent gets them resolved per task and discards them when the task ends. No standing access, no leaks across runs.</dd>
			</div>
		</dl>
	</section>

	<!-- On-disk example -->
	<section class="mb-16 sm:mb-20 text-center">
		<h2 class="text-xs font-medium text-text-muted uppercase tracking-widest mb-4">What a module looks like on disk</h2>
		<pre class="bg-bg-raised border border-border text-sm text-text-secondary p-5 overflow-x-auto leading-relaxed text-left max-w-lg mx-auto"><code>crm/
  module.yaml      # name, secrets, dependencies
  llms.txt         # the agent's reading list
  info.md          # what this module is for
  schema.md        # the database tables
  runbooks/
    list-customers.md
    refund-flow.md</code></pre>
		<p class="text-sm text-text-muted italic mt-4">That folder is the deliverable.</p>
	</section>

	<!-- Try it yourself -->
	<section class="mb-16 sm:mb-20 text-center">
		<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-text mb-6">Try it yourself.</h2>
		<a
			href="/product"
			class="inline-block bg-accent text-bg text-sm font-medium px-6 py-3 hover:bg-accent-hover transition-colors"
		>
			Open ContextAgora
		</a>
	</section>

</Base>
